  <span id="freeText5175065873692446851" style="display:none"><i>Fatal Vision</i> follows the real life story of Doctor Jeffrey MacDonald, and the murder of his wife and children. On 17th February 1970, MacDonald claims that a group of hippies, two white men, a black man and a blonde woman with a floppy hat, broke into his house, assaulted him, and then murdered his wife and two little girls. But as law enforcement investigate further, his story doesn't seem to ring true, and physical evidence doesn't match his claims. Could MacDonald, respected Green Beret doctor and seemingly loving husband and father, actually be the true killer? <br><br>So I was very familiar with this story going into this book, as I believe it was mentioned on an episode of <i>My Favorite Murder</i>, and already had my own opinion before I read this book. My opinion didn't change throughout reading, and if anything, further cemented my opinion. My verdict?<br><br><img src="https://images.gr-assets.com/hostedimages/1530120427ra/25867738.gif" class="gr-hostedUserImg"><br><br>However, it was interesting getting to know more about this case, and following McGinnis as he interacted with MacDonald, and watching him realise that this guy he believed to be innocent, was kinda shady, and probably, almost definitely murdered his family. POS. <br><br>Overall, great read!</span>
